Chapter 7 Homework

In Chapter 5, we briefly explored data on the salaries of engineering graduates from the National Science Foundation 2017 National Survey of College Graduates from a univariate perspective. Now, lets explore the relationships between multiple variables.

When a question asks you to make a plot, remember to set a theme, title, subtitle, labels, colors, etc. It is up to you how to personalize your plots, but put in some effort, and make the plotting approach consistent throughout the document. For example, you could use the same theme for all plots. I also like to use the subtitle as a place for the main summary for the viewer.

Assign this to a dataframe object with a meaningful name.

Question 6: Cumulative distribution function

Plot the cumulative distribution function of salary by gender. Adjust the x-axis with scale_x_log10(limits = c(5e4, 5e5)) to zoom in a bit. What do you notice about the salaries for men and women? Hint: Remember there are greater differences the farther up you go on a log scale axis.

Question 8: Hypothetical analysis

Think about what other variables you would like to include in an hypothetical analysis. From your perspective, what are the most important individual, family, and workforce factors related to salarybeyond gender and age?

In a broader analysis of engineering salaries, I would include variables that capture individual, family, and workplace factors beyond gender and age. At the individual level, education, experience, certifications, and technical skills are major determinants of pay. Family characteristics such as marital status, dependents, and caregiving responsibilities may influence work choices and career progression. Workforce factorsincluding industry sector, company size, region, and job titlealso shape salary outcomes by reflecting differences in demand, cost of living, and advancement opportunities. Considering these variables together would provide a more complete understanding of what drives salary differences among engineers.

Recreate this plot with the mpg dataset. Remember to use ?mpg for information on the dataset and the variables. How would you describe the correlation between the independent variable and dependent variable? Do you see any patterns when considering the third variable?

# set global options for figures, code, warnings, and messages
knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width=6, fig.height=4, fig.path="../figs/",
                      echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE)
# load packages for current session
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(knitr)
library(scales)
options(scipen = 999)

me_clean <- read_csv("ME_salaries.csv") |>
  janitor::clean_names() |>              
  mutate(
    gender = as.factor(gender)           
  ) |>
  filter(salary != 0)                    


# number of observations with salary as 0 
me_zero_salary <- read_csv("ME_salaries.csv") |>
  janitor::clean_names() |>
  filter(salary == 0)

n_zero_salary <- nrow(me_zero_salary)
n_zero_salary
# number of factor levels
levels(me_clean$gender)
# univariate eda
theme_set(theme_minimal())

glimpse(me_clean)

me_clean |>
ggplot(aes(x = age)) +
geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, fill = "steelblue", color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
labs(
title = "Distribution of Age among Engineering Graduates",
subtitle = "Most respondents are between their late 20s and 40s",
x = "Age (years)", y = "Count"
)

me_clean |>
summarize(
mean_age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE),
median_age = median(age, na.rm = TRUE),
sd_age = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE),
min_age = min(age, na.rm = TRUE),
max_age = max(age, na.rm = TRUE)
) |>
kable()

me_clean |>
count(gender) |>
mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) |>
ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = prop, fill = gender)) +
geom_col(alpha = 0.8) +
scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
labs(
title = "Gender Distribution of Engineering Graduates",
subtitle = "Proportion of respondents by gender",
x = "Gender", y = "Percent"
) +
theme(legend.position = "none")

me_clean |>
ggplot(aes(x = salary)) +
geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, fill = "darkseagreen", color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
labs(
title = "Distribution of Engineering Salaries (2017)",
subtitle = "Right-skewed distribution; many between $60k$120k",
x = "Annual Salary (USD)", y = "Count"
)

me_clean |>
summarize(
mean_salary = mean(salary, na.rm = TRUE),
median_salary = median(salary, na.rm = TRUE),
sd_salary = sd(salary, na.rm = TRUE),
min_salary = min(salary, na.rm = TRUE),
max_salary = max(salary, na.rm = TRUE)
) |>
kable()

# histogram of salaries split by gender
me_clean |>
ggplot(aes(x = salary, fill = gender)) +
geom_histogram(bins = 50, color = "lightgrey", alpha = 0.8) +
facet_wrap(~ gender) +
labs(
title = "Distribution of Engineering Salaries by Gender",
subtitle = "Histogram faceted by gender, 50 bins, light grey outlines",
x = "Annual Salary (USD)",
y = "Count",
fill = "Gender"
) +
theme_minimal()

# histogram of ages split by gender
me_clean |>
  ggplot(aes(x = age, fill = gender)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50, color = "lightgrey", alpha = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ gender) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Age by Gender",
    subtitle = "Histogram faceted by gender, 50 bins, light grey outlines",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Count",
    fill = "Gender"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# boxplots of salary data by gender
me_clean |>
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = salary, fill = gender)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = 1, alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ gender) +
  labs(
    title = "Boxplot of Salary by Gender",
    subtitle = "Boxplots faceted by gender with hollow-circle outliers",
    x = "Gender",
    y = "Annual Salary (USD)",
    fill = "Gender"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# boxplots of age data by gender
me_clean |>
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = age, fill = gender)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = 1, alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ gender) +
  labs(
    title = "Boxplot of Age by Gender",
    subtitle = "Boxplots faceted by gender with hollow-circle outliers",
    x = "Gender",
    y = "Age (years)",
    fill = "Gender"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# scatterplot of salary across age by gender
me_clean |>
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = salary, color = gender)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(
    title = "Scatterplot of Age vs. Salary by Gender",
    subtitle = "Each point represents one respondent; color differentiates gender",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Annual Salary (USD)",
    color = "Gender"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# correlation test
cor_test_result <- cor.test(me_clean$age, me_clean$salary, method = "pearson")

cor_test_result
# plot cdf of salary by gender

me_clean |>
  ggplot(aes(x = salary, color = gender)) +
  stat_ecdf(size = 1) +
  scale_x_log10(limits = c(5e4, 5e5)) +
  labs(
    title = "Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF) of Salary by Gender",
    subtitle = "CDF plotted on a log10 scale to highlight upper-salary differences",
    x = "Annual Salary (USD, log10 scale)",
    y = "Cumulative Proportion",
    color = "Gender"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# calculate quantiles of salary by gender

q_salary_gender <- me_clean |>
  group_by(gender) |>
  summarize(
    n   = n(),
    q00 = quantile(salary, 0.00, na.rm = TRUE),
    q25 = quantile(salary, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE),
    q50 = quantile(salary, 0.50, na.rm = TRUE),  # median
    q75 = quantile(salary, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    q90 = quantile(salary, 0.90, na.rm = TRUE),
    q95 = quantile(salary, 0.95, na.rm = TRUE),
    q100= quantile(salary, 1.00, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

# Nicely formatted table (no scientific notation)
q_salary_gender_fmt <- q_salary_gender |>
  mutate(across(starts_with("q"), function(x) scales::dollar(x)))

knitr::kable(q_salary_gender_fmt, caption = "Salary quantiles by gender")
